sec.p:
Despite advances in the production of various enzymes by employing genetic engineering techniques, the preparation of some enzymes still relies on extraction from natural resources such as papain, ficain, bromelain, and peroxidase (POX), which are all of plant origin 

. POX (EC.1.11.1.x) is a ubiquitous oxidoreductase with the ability to reduce one molecule of hydrogen peroxide to two molecules of water at the expense of oxidizing two reducing molecules (

). This ability, in addition to its affinity for a broad spectrum of reducing species, has endowed POXs with the possibility of participating in vital physiological processes in various organisms and to find versatile applications in different industries (

). An important subgroup of the POX superfamily belongs to Class III plant POXs (EC 1.11.1.7), which are extracellular enzymes 

). Due to its accessibility, stability, and important applications, horseradish peroxidase (HRP) has already reached the market (

).

The large-scale preparation of HRP relies on horseradish cultivation, which is currently ongoing in several countries (

). The global HRP market was valued at approximately 38 million USD in 2018, and it is anticipated to reach 73 million USD by the end of 2025, growing by approximately 8.5% annually during 2019–2025 (

). However, the seasonal availability of horseradish combined with low yields makes this method of HRP production problematic. In addition to the cultivation hassle, the current large-scale production of HRP offers mainly 
one type
of this enzyme (mainly HRP-C) (

).

As the research proceeds, the POX applications have also expanded, ranging from the pulp, paper, textile, and polymer industries to immunoassays, analytical, bioanalytical and diagnostic kits as well as biosensor fabrication, wastewater treatment, etc. (

). Concomitantly, the anticipated possible POX applications have increased the demand for miscellaneous POXs with diverse operational stabilities, substrate spectra, and pH tolerances. This trend has worked as the driving force behind the ongoing research on different POXs (

).

In contrast to the classical method of HRP production, some biotechnology-based methods, such as plant cell and hairy root culture, are bioreactor-dependent technologies (

). These approaches allow us to bypass the biological growth period of the plant as well as its agricultural difficulties. Therefore, the desired product is built up under controlled 
in vitro
conditions and harvested at the end of each subculture. Plant cell and tissue culture not only boosted the search for novel POXs but also improve the current knowledge about these important enzymes from both an applied and physiological point of view (

; 

). In fact, studies on peanut (

Arachis hypogaea

) cell culture resulted in the first POX crystallography report (

). There are still serious challenges ahead for plant cell culture to be used in cost-effective large-scale production plans (

), however, advances in this field are promising (

).

POXalf
was purified to homogeneity, as verified by 
SDS
– 
PAGE
(
Fig. 2A
), through a 4-step procedure. The quantified results of this method are summarized in 
Table 1
. The salt precipitation step removed approximately 31% of the undesirable proteins from the raw extract, with a less than 10% loss of POX activity (
Table 1
). Although size exclusion chromatography (
Fig. 2B
) gave rise to a 3-fold purification, it was the cation-exchange chromatography on S-Sepharose (
Fig. 2C
) that resulted in 117-fold purification of 
POXalf
. The UV–visible spectrum of the purified enzyme (
Fig. 2D
) showed the characteristic absorption band of the haem group of plant class III-POXs (

) with a Reinheitszah ratio (RZ = A402/A280) value of 0.57, close to the RZ value of soybean POXs (0.5) (

), 

O. basilicum

(0.67) (

), and tomato POX (0.7) (

).

In parallel with the structural analysis results (presented in the next section), an average molecular weight of 33.5 ± 1 kD was determined for POXalf from its SDS – PAGE analysis ( Fig. 2A ). This is close to the MW of the cationic POXs of
Eruca vesicaria
leaves (34 kD) (
) and the
Nicotiana tubacum
cell culture (34 kD) (
). Two-dimensional gel isoelectric focusing (2-D gel IEF, Fig. 3A ), revealed that POXalf was a mixture of several cationic POXs with close MWs and PI ranging from 9 to 10. A similar range of PI was reported for some other cationic POXs, such as garlic (
Allium sativum L
) POXs (
) and POX isozymes obtained from the cell culture of tobacco (
).

The optimal pH of POX activity may vary from one substrate to another because the changes in pH influence the redox potentials of both the substrate and the intermediate I [oxyferryl haem (Fe IV ––O) cation radical], which is formed after a reaction of H 2 O 2 with a POX (
). Fig. 3B indicates that POXalf showed its optimal activity at pH 5.5 and maintained 75% of its optimal activity between pH 4.5 and 7 in the presence of phenol. Changing the substrate from phenol to guaiacol shifted the range of the optimal pH to 3.5 to 6, while there were no significant changes in the optimal activity. Although a few plant POXs, such as POX of
Jatropha curcas
leaves (
), could maintain their optimal activities over a wider range of pH values, many plant POXs show sharp activity drops within a ≤1 unit change around the optimal pH, such as cationic POXs of
Brassica oleracea ( Thongsook and Barrett, 2005 )
and sorghum grain (
). It is also understood from Fig. 3C that POXalf tolerates high temperatures during the assay period, but it is not stable above 50 ◦ C ( Fig. 3D ), regardless of the substrate identity. Similar feedback to the temperature changes has been reported for many POXs, including those of sorghum grain (
) and
Eruca vesicaria ( Nadaroglu et al., 2013 )
. Examination of the shelf life of the POXalf solution at 4 ◦ C revealed its high stability at the examined temperature, as there was only a 15% decrease in the functional stability of the enzyme after 2 years ( Fig. 3E and F ).

To examine the ability of POXalf to oxidize different types of substrates, synthetic phenolic, catecholic, guaiacolic, and aniline derivatives of the diazo dyes, illustrated in Fig. 4 , were reacted with POXalf in the presence of H 2 O 2 . Using this diazo skeleton allowed us to control both the structural and electronic changes in the derivatives. In addition, the course of the enzymatic reactions could be followed spectrophotometrically (
). These examinations revealed that POXalf was able to oxidize phenolic, guaiacolic, and catecholic azo derivatives ( Fig. S2 , Supplementary document). It has been demonstrated that HRP can oxidize all of the structures illustrated in Fig. 4 , including IV and V (
). However, the reactions of POXalf with monoamines (structure IV) were slow ( Fig. S2D , supplementary document), and reactions with structure V did not proceed. Unlike HRP but similar to cationic POXpnt , POXalf had little effect on indole-3-acetic acid (IAA) ( Fig. S2E , supplementary document). This suggests that POXalf might have no direct impact on the regulation of IAA homeostasis (
). However, similar to other plant POXs, POXalf could easily oxidize ascorbate ( Fig. S2F , Supplementary document).

The kinetic parameters of POXalf for phenol, guaiacol, H 2 O 2 and KCN are shown in Table 2 . This data promotes the practical importance of POXalf . A specific activity of 4320.5 AU mg 1 (in the presence of phenol) was reported for POXalf , which was approximately 20 times higher than the corresponding specific activity reported for commercial HRP (206 AU mg 1 ) (
). This high specific activity could be behind the significant difference between the POX activities illustrated in Fig. 1C . However, Table 2 shows the higher affinity of POXalf towards guaiacol with a fast rate of reaction. This gives guaiacol a specificity constant more than 100 times higher than that of phenol in its reaction with POXalf . These data reveal significantly different specific activities of POXalf compared with those of HRP and POXpnt (
).

Similar to other plant type-III POXs, POXalf was inhibited at higher concentrations of H 2 O 2 as well as by KCN. However, the high IC50 value of H 2 O 2 revealed the remarkable functional stability of POXalf in the presence of this suicide substrate. The Km values of POXalf for guaiacol and H 2 O 2 are comparable to the Km values reported for cationic POXs of garlic (9.5 and 2 mM) (
) and broccoli (8.8 and 9.73 mM) (
), respectively. Possible roles of cationic POXs in the metabolism of monolignols have been documented (
). Considering the dynamics of POXalf production ( Fig. 1D ), its inactivity towards IAA and its high affinity for guaiacol support the assumption that this cationic enzyme might have associated roles with
A. frigida
cell wall construction and the regulation of cell wall plasticity.

BLAST of the POXalf sequence against the protein database had 3 hits, including 1SCH (
), 5TWT (
), and 1PA2 (
) with a sequence identity of 70.65, 64.16, and 49.67% belonging to
A. hypogaea
(peanut),
Panicum virgatum
(switchgrass), and
A. thaliana
, respectively. Therefore, 1SCH was selected as the template for the homology modelling. Accordingly, 6 models were built with the genetic Algorithm 341 (GA341) score of 1.0. Although all of the predicted models had close discrete optimized protein energy (DOPE) scores close to 30000, the model with the least Modeller objective function (molpdf) score of 1571.79 was selected for POXalf ( Fig. 5A ). The structure was validated by ProSA tools. The Z score of the model (8.26) was in the range of the structures identified by X-ray diffraction ( Fig. S4A , Supplementary document). The Ramachandran plot of the POXalf model revealed that 96.22 and 2.40% of the amino acid residues were in favoured and acceptable conformations, respectively, while only 1.38% of the residues were experiencing steric strain ( Fig. S4B , Supplementary document). The quality of the model structure was further assessed by a Verify3D program that investigated the folding compatibility of the atomic Model (3D) with its own amino acid sequence (1D). The resulting profile of the residues ( Fig. S4C , Supplementary document) had scores between 0.1 and 0.71, while 97.95% of the residues had an average 3D–1D score > 0.2. The compatibility score > 0 in a VERIFY3D graph corresponds to an acceptable side-chain environment (
).

2.4.3.1. Overall fold of POXalf .
The core fold of plant POXs is similar due to the special topological arrangement of the 10 α- helices, designated by letters from A to J, but they are usually accompanied by some variable helices. For instance, there are two more short helices after helix B ( Fig. 5B , in salmon colour) in both the POXalf and HRP structures, while POXpnt contains only helix B (
). These differences make the total number of helices in plant POXs dissimilar, with 13 in POXpnt , 15 in POXalf and 16 in HRP ( Fig. 5B ). Key residues for the catalytic activity of a plant POX reside on helices B and F, which are located on two sides (distal and proximal, respectively) of the haem group ( Fig. 5A , in green colour). Although the β- strands do not play a significant role in the overall folding of plant POXs, a short antiparallel β- sheet is observed near the haem group, i.e., residues 174–176 and 209–211 in POXalf ( Fig. 5A , in purple colour) and 173–175 and 210–212 in POXpnt (
).

2.4.3.2. Disulfide bonds, salt bridge, and calcium ions. The functional stability of the POXalf solution at 4 ◦ C over 2 years is illustrated in Fig. 3E and F . Plant POX folding owes its stability to some structural elements that support the scaffold of the enzyme against the hydrodynamic pressure of the solution. Four conserved disulfide bonds and one salt bridge ( Table S2 , Supplementary document) remarkably decreased the degrees of freedom of the structural components of the enzyme. The disulfide bonds of C10–C90, C43–C48, C96–C289, and C175–C 200 in POXalf ( Fig. 5A in yellow colour) match the C11–C91, C44–C49, C97–C290, C176–C201 and C11–C91, C44–C49, C97–C301, C177–C209 bonds in POXpnt and HRP-C1, respectively (
;
). D98 and R 122 in POXalf also build the salt bridge (2.89 Å, Table S2 ) between the helix D and the adjacent loop. This is achieved by D99- R 123 in both POXpnt (2.82 Å) and HRP-C1 (2.90 Å).

2.4.3.3. Prosthetic group of haem (iron III protoporphyrin IX).
The haem group of a plant POX occupies the central space between helices B and F. It anchors to the protein skeleton by strong H-bonds of its propionate moieties with a few conserved residues. However, small differences are observed in the arrangements of the H-bonds. In POXalf , R 30 and R 174 produce strong double-interactions with each of the propionate moieties of the haem group ( Table S2 and Fig. 5A in purple). The stabilizing effects of these bonds are seen in the RMSF plot of POXalf ( Fig. 6B ). In fact, the impact of these interactions on the overall stability of POXalf is comparable with those of the salt bridge and Ca ions ( Fig. 6B ). A similar arrangement is observed in POXpnt , where R 31, S35, and Q175 participate in H-bonds with haem propionates (2.95, 2.86, and 2.98 Å, respectively), while S73 and R 75 stand further at distances of 4.76 and 4.03 Å (
).

The correct position of the haem in the active site of a plant POX is mainly tuned through interactions with the residing residues on helices B and F. Helix B, on the distal side, consists of approximately 13 amino acids, including conserved R 38, H42, and F40 (in HRP), which play essential roles in both the function and stability of haem ( Fig. 5A ) (
;
). Helix F is located almost below the haem in the proximal section and provides the prosthetic group with the conserved H167 (in HRP). The possible roles of R 38, H42, and H167 (equal to R 37, H41, and H 168 in POXalf , Table S2 ) have been well discussed in the literature. However, the debates on possible roles of helix F have not been conclusive since the crystallographic data reveal larger variations in the number of total residues of helix F compared with that of helix B (e.g., 13, 15, and 7 in HRP, palm POX, and POXpnt , respectively) in addition to the variable helices after helix F (named F ′ , F ′′ , F ′′ 2, Fig. 5B in green) (
).

4-Aminoantipyrine (4AAP), 2,4-dichlorophenoxyacetic acid, kinetin, and phenylmethylsulfonyl fluoride (PMSF) were purchased from SigmaTM Chemical and Biochemical Company (St. Louis, MO, USA ). Guaiacol was from Fluka Chemie GmbH. Folin-Ciocalteu reagent, ABTS, and ammonium sulfate were purchased from Merck (Darmstadt, Germany ). Azo dyes ( Fig. 4 ) were synthesized as described previously (
). Solid Murashige and Skoog medium (MS) was prepared according to the literature using 8 g L 1 agar (
).
Alkanna frigida Boiss. (Boraginaceae)
samples were collected from Sheikh Shab˜an (
32 ◦ 35 ′ 06.3 ′′ N
50 ◦ 36 ′ 02.7 ′′ E
) in Charmahal Bakhtiyari Province of Iran in mid-July, and the plant specimens were identified by the botanist of the scientific board of the Iran Research Institute of Forests and Range Lands, Professor Dr. V . Mozaffarian. The statistical analysis was performed using Microsoft Excel software, and the results are presented as the mean ± standard error.

The proliferated
A. frigida
callus was sampled at different time intervals during a 31-day subculture. The samples were subjected to concomitant POX and CAT assays. First, at 4 ◦ C, pieces of fresh callus ( 1 g ) were crushed and ground in a porcelain mortar containing 3 mL of extraction buffer [Tris base (10 mM, pH 6.0) containing PMSF (0.55 μM)]. The resulting mixture was filtered, and the filtrate (100 μL) was immediately assayed spectrophotometrically (at 510 nm ) for POX activity in the presence of phenol (8.6 mM), 4AAP (39.4 mM), and H 2 O 2 (6.76 mM) in phosphate buffer solution (PBS 10 mM, pH 6.8) at 20 ◦ C. The extinction coefficient of the quinone-imine product ( 6500 cm 1 M 1 ) was used in the relevant calculations (
). A spectrophotometric assay of CAT activity (at 240 nm ) was carried out with 100 μL of the filtrate in PBS (10 mM, pH 6.8) containing H 2 O 2 (10 mM) (
). The standard curves [ Fig. S1 , Supplementary Document] obtained for commercial HRP-C [Merck (Darmstadt, Germany )] and CAT [Serva electrophoresis GmbH (D-69115 Heidelberg)] were used to calculate the results in terms of mg of POX and CAT per gram of wet callus. All spectrophotometric measurements were carried out using a UV/Visible Specord 50+ spectrophotometer (Analytik Jena, Germany ).

The protein content of the desired solutions was measured by the Bradford method. PAGE and SDS–PAGE of the samples were performed according to the conventional Laemmli method using a resolving (12.5%) and stacking (4%) polyacrylamide gel at a constant electrophoretic field of 200 V. The protein bands were visualized by both Coomassie brilliant blue R250 and AgNO 3 staining methods. To perform high-resolution 2D gel electrophoresis, isoelectric focusing (IEF) was conducted as described earlier (
). The second dimension electrophoretic separation was carried out on a 12.5% gel according to the Laemmli method (
).

Important physicochemical properties of the purified POXalf , including optimal pH, optimal temperature, thermal stability, operational stability, substrate spectrum (reactivity), inhibition, and relevant kinetics parameters, were measured spectrophotometrically in a conventional UV–visible quartz cell in a total volume of 3 mL using PBS (10 mM, at the desired pH) as the reaction medium using the desired organic substrate. In addition to phenol (mentioned above), guaiacol was also used as the organic substrate in some kinetics studies on POXalf . Subsequently, the formation of the chromophoric product ( ε = 26,600 cm 1 M 1 ) was followed at 470 nm (
). Additional information about the experiments is mentioned in the captions of the corresponding data. The kinetics parameters of the substrates were extracted from Lineweaver-Burk analysis of the corresponding velocity curves under steady-state conditions, and the inhibition constants were obtained from the fitted equations of the inhibition graphs as well as by using the Cheng–Prusoff equation (
): IC50 = Ki [1 + [S]/ Km ]. The results of the kinetic studies are the average of at least triplicate measurements. A unit of activity is equal to the formation of the chromophoric product (1 μM min 1 ).

The 3D structure of 
POXalf
was predicted via homology modelling by Modeller 9v19, while the 3D structure of 
POXpnt
(PDB ID: 1SCHA) was used as the template (

). To evaluate the predicted 3D model structure, a Ramachandran plot was constructed using the PROCHECK server (http://services.mbi.ucla.edu/PROCHECK) through the SAVE server (http://services.mbi.ucla.edu/SAVES). The ProSA web server (https://prosa.services.came.sbg.ac.at/prosa.pHp) was used to calculate the Z score. The model structure was further evaluated with the VERIFY3D server by assessing the compatibility of each amino acid residue with the local 3D structure by averaging the 3D–1D score (

). Molecular dynamics (MD) simulation was used to refine the structures obtained from homology modelling. Structural refinement was performed using GROMACS 4.6.3. To run the simulation, previously reported conditions and settings for analysis were applied (

). See the Supplementary document for the experimental details. Visualization and analysis of molecular structures were performed by UCSF Chimera 1.10.2 and web-based iCn3D (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Structure/icn3d/full.html).

